The European "Green Deal"
NEW YORK – Europe has done it.
The "Green Pact for Europe" announced by the European Commission is to date the first global sustainable development plan decided by a major region of the planet.
It thus becomes a landmark for the world – a guide to transformation towards a prosperous, socially inclusive, and environmentally sustainable economy, a first agenda, for all, to achieve it.
Of course, the task awaiting Europeans is impressive.
Even the reading of documents that have just been made public is: a profusion at first glance of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy, a large number of involved and related subjects, ranging from energy to transport, from food to industry.
His critics will mock European bureaucracy.
But it is a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense of the term: it is rational.
The sustainable development goals are clearly stated, the targets are defined in line with objectives subject to a deadline, and the programs and procedures are adapted to the targets.
Overall, the ambition displayed is to achieve "carbon neutrality" (net zero emissions of greenhouse gases) by 2050, to establish a circular economy that puts an end to the destructive pollution caused by plastics and other petrochemical derivatives, pesticides, and toxic waste, to establish a "farm-to-table" food system that does not kill people by making them eat overly processed products by the industry, nor kill the earth with non-sustainable agricultural practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method to achieve this must rely on the citizens themselves.
Once again, detractors will consider announcements of public consultations as mere window-dressing for dreamers.
But let's talk about useless chatter to French President Emmanuel Macron, who has been facing protests turning into riots for over a year, or to Chilean President Sebastián Piñera, whose country suddenly rose up this autumn, after a slight increase in subway ticket prices.
Macron and Piñera are both convinced of the need for ecological change.
Both have committed to carbon neutrality in their respective countries by 2050.
And both are desperately trying to figure out how to organize or structure a public consultation, but after the fact.
American proponents of neoliberalism will once again mock, and claim that the "market" will know how to remedy climate change.
But one only has to look at the United States today.
If neoliberalism treats the planet the way it has treated American infrastructure, we all have reason to worry.
Deplaning at an American airport is to have to deal with elevators, escalators, broken shuttle buses, taxis that don't show up, non-existent rail connections, highways, whose lines are in such bad condition that you can't drive on them, replaced by detours.
The reason for these malfunctions is simple: corruption.
Each American electoral cycle now costs $8 billion, if not more, and its funding is assured by billionaires, large oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and groups determined to lower taxes and at all costs protect the status quo.
Market solutions are a joke when policy is subject to all the influences that come from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Pact shows a government as it should be, not a government subordinate to the interests of businesses.
The European Green Deal in fact provides an operational demonstration of the success of European social democracy (in its non-partisan operational sense).
A mixed economy, combining markets, state regulatory power, the public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public objectives, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships and an informed population.
In fact, it's an industrial policy at its most sophisticated level.
(I have recently outlined, in broad terms, what a social democratic Green New Deal strategy would look like for the United States.)
We have reasons to be optimistic.
The most important point is that advanced technologies, which will enable the creation of a decarbonized, resource-efficient, and therefore ecologically sustainable advanced economy, exist, either at the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
By combining renewable energy, digital technologies, cutting-edge materials, and collaborative economies in transportation or other infrastructure, we can decarbonize the energy system, transition to a circular economy, and drastically reduce primary resource flows.
But we must to that overcome three major challenges.
The first is to overcome the interests that seek to maintain the status quo.
The major oil companies will have to absorb the losses, but oil workers and mining regions should receive compensation in the form of income support, retraining through training, and other public aid.
The European plan rightly claims a "just transition".
The second challenge is that of financing.
Europe, like the other regions of the world, will have to redirect a relatively small part of its production, 1% to 2%, towards the green economy, namely new infrastructure, public markets, research and development, industrial equipment renewal, etc. Financing will come from the private sector, but also from public budgets.
Europe must stand up to ideologues who oppose an increase in EU spending.
The facts will have to be taken into account.
The biggest challenge is diplomatic.
Europe accounts for roughly 9.1% of global carbon dioxide emissions, when China's share is around 30% and that of the United States is 14%.
Even if Europe manages to fully implement its green pact, it will be to no avail if the other regions of the world do not join in its fight.
European leaders therefore rightly consider diplomacy to be fundamental to the success of the green pact.
Let's take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's leading emitter of CO2 (though its emissions per capita remain two times lower than those of the United States).
China, on its own, will determine the future of the global climate.
On the one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if it doesn't make enough efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must face the dangers of the unfortunate Cold War launched by America.
Hardliners within the government and Chinese coal lobbies resist decarbonization, under pressure from the US, especially since Trump rejects it himself.
European diplomacy can make a difference if it refuses to subscribe to America's underhanded measures to restrain China and instead proposes a positive and unambiguous partnership to it: working together on the establishment of infrastructure, sustainable development and technology in Eurasia, within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to that of Europe.
Such a partnership would be of immense benefit for Europe, China, and the dozen Eurasian countries that separate them, not to mention the world at large.
Europe has taken a historic step with its ambitious, mobilizing, and achievable plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainty and instability.
